For example, we have counted more than 8000 institutions in the health field during the last ten years, most of them are private.

There is also a great effort aimed at developing Sana’a Old City through the initiative of Yemeni ambassador in London Mr. Mohammed al-Wadhhi – in collaboration with Queen Rania Foundation in Jordan, British Council and others, where they are able to preserve the wealth of buildings in Yemen. This is one example of the work done to preserve the civilization heritage in Yemen.

Yemen Investment and Development conference starts tomorrow. Do you think, that this conference will live up to its expectations?

There is no doubt that this fruitful conference will bring a lot of positive effects and benefits, both for Yemen and investors. Throughout this conference, the ones who will take it will be the investors. So, if investors will benefit from the conference and everybody is also asking for my opinion on that. I say that we should see what they have to show and what they have to say, instead of asking for my opinion on what they will talk about. One thing I can guarantee whomsoever will attend the conference: It is done in a professional manner; the preparations for the exhibition is done in a most remarkable fashion.
